</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Advances in medical diagnosis reveal that coronary artery aneurysms (CAAs) may develop in several clinical scenarios and manifest variable symptoms, imaging appearances, and outcomes. Aneurysms are pathologically classified into three groups: atherosclerotic, inflammatory, and noninflammatory. The last category is associated with congenital, inherited, and connective tissue disorders. Overlap exists among the groups, because secondary atherosclerotic change may be present in an aneurysm of any cause. Atherosclerosis is the most common cause of CAAs in adults, and inflammation is considered the underlying mechanism. In children, Kawasaki disease is the most likely cause of CAAs. In both conditions, the aneurysms are usually multiple and affect more than one coronary artery. Mycotic (infectious), iatrogenic, and cocaine-induced CAAs are also well documented. Most CAAs are discovered incidentally, but potential cardiovascular complications include thrombosis, occlusion, fistula formation, rupture, myocardial infarction, and cardiac tamponade. Imaging modalities to evaluate a suspected CAA include transthoracic echocardiography, angiographic cardiac catheterization, electrocardiographically gated computed tomographic angiography, cardiac magnetic resonance (MR) imaging, and MR angiography. Management is usually individualized, and options include surveillance, anticoagulant therapy, percutaneous stent or coil placement, surgical resection, and coronary artery bypass grafting.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170175">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170175">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig1a.jpeg" height="1273" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Isolated noninflammatory true aneurysm in a 68-year-old woman who presented with chest tightness after physical activity. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> computed tomographic (CT) angiographic images show a large, partially thrombosed mass (arrow) superior to the left ventricle and abutting the main pulmonary artery <i>(Pulm Art)</i>. A branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery (LAD) (arrowhead) leads directly to the enhancing portion of the mass. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of sections of the gross specimen obtained at resection helps confirm the finding of a CAA with organized thrombus. (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig1b.jpeg" height="1300" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Isolated noninflammatory true aneurysm in a 68-year-old woman who presented with chest tightness after physical activity. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> computed tomographic (CT) angiographic images show a large, partially thrombosed mass (arrow) superior to the left ventricle and abutting the main pulmonary artery <i>(Pulm Art)</i>. A branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery (LAD) (arrowhead) leads directly to the enhancing portion of the mass. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of sections of the gross specimen obtained at resection helps confirm the finding of a CAA with organized thrombus. (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig1c.jpeg" height="730" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Isolated noninflammatory true aneurysm in a 68-year-old woman who presented with chest tightness after physical activity. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> computed tomographic (CT) angiographic images show a large, partially thrombosed mass (arrow) superior to the left ventricle and abutting the main pulmonary artery <i>(Pulm Art)</i>. A branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery (LAD) (arrowhead) leads directly to the enhancing portion of the mass. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of sections of the gross specimen obtained at resection helps confirm the finding of a CAA with organized thrombus. (Scale is in centimeters.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig2.jpeg" height="3200" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. ACAA with nonspecific histopathologic findings. Top: Low-power photomicrograph of the surgical specimen shows thinning of the media (arrows). The intima <i>(INT)</i> is thickened with fibrous tissue. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×40.) Middle: High-power photomicrograph shows a surface thrombus <i>(THR)</i>. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.) Bottom: High-power photomicrograph shows an atherosclerotic lesion (arrows), a calcified fibroatheroma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig3a.jpeg" height="1265" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. ACAA, with rupture into the right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Postmortem radiograph of a dissected vascular specimen obtained after injection of barium contrast material shows a disrupted aneurysm (arrows) in the proximal RCA. <i>LCX</i> = left circumflex coronary artery, <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen of the right ventricle obtained after postmortem injection of barium contrast material shows that extravasation of the contrast material (white material along the chordae of the tricuspid valve) has resulted from rupture of an aneurysm of the RCA into the right ventricle (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig3b.jpeg" height="1271" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. ACAA, with rupture into the right ventricle. <b>(a)</b> Postmortem radiograph of a dissected vascular specimen obtained after injection of barium contrast material shows a disrupted aneurysm (arrows) in the proximal RCA. <i>LCX</i> = left circumflex coronary artery, <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen of the right ventricle obtained after postmortem injection of barium contrast material shows that extravasation of the contrast material (white material along the chordae of the tricuspid valve) has resulted from rupture of an aneurysm of the RCA into the right ventricle (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig4a.jpeg" height="2430" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 5-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows a gross heart specimen (top) in the subacute phase that shows diffuse ectasia of the LAD and the left diagonal artery <i>(LD)</i>. The two rows of cut specimens (bottom) show serial cross sections of a gross specimen of a thrombosed, dilated aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the artery wall, which is replaced by inflammation, with destruction of the media. The lumen is at the right (blood). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig4b.jpeg" height="1115" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 5-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows a gross heart specimen (top) in the subacute phase that shows diffuse ectasia of the LAD and the left diagonal artery <i>(LD)</i>. The two rows of cut specimens (bottom) show serial cross sections of a gross specimen of a thrombosed, dilated aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the artery wall, which is replaced by inflammation, with destruction of the media. The lumen is at the right (blood). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig5.jpeg" height="1390" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Idiopathic aneurysm of the RCA. Photograph of the cut surface of the gross specimen shows white plastic probes indicating a normal coronary artery on either side of the aneurysm (in the center), which is filled with thrombus. The aneurysm wall is composed of fibrous tissue and thinned media without atherosclerotic change. (Scale is in centimeters.) (Courtesy of Joseph J. Maleszewski, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig6a.jpeg" height="1310" width="1304" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. ACAA in a 67-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image of the RCA shows a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the RCA, as well as diffuse luminal irregularity (arrowheads) of the mid and distal portions of the RCA. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a focal outpouching (arrow) of the proximal RCA. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT angiographic maximum intensity projection in the same projection as in <b>a</b> also shows a saccular aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig6b.jpeg" height="1310" width="1147" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. ACAA in a 67-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image of the RCA shows a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the RCA, as well as diffuse luminal irregularity (arrowheads) of the mid and distal portions of the RCA. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a focal outpouching (arrow) of the proximal RCA. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT angiographic maximum intensity projection in the same projection as in <b>a</b> also shows a saccular aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig6c.jpeg" height="1310" width="1246" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. ACAA in a 67-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image of the RCA shows a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the RCA, as well as diffuse luminal irregularity (arrowheads) of the mid and distal portions of the RCA. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a focal outpouching (arrow) of the proximal RCA. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT angiographic maximum intensity projection in the same projection as in <b>a</b> also shows a saccular aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig7a.jpeg" height="1325" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. ACAA in a 68-year-old man with unstable angina. Oblique sagittal <b>(a)</b> and oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> multiplanar reconstruction (MPR) CT angiographic images show fusiform dilatation of the LAD, with multifocal atherosclerotic plaque (arrow). Extensive mural thrombus (<b>*</b>) is depicted in the involved segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig7b.jpeg" height="1325" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. ACAA in a 68-year-old man with unstable angina. Oblique sagittal <b>(a)</b> and oblique coronal <b>(b)</b> multiplanar reconstruction (MPR) CT angiographic images show fusiform dilatation of the LAD, with multifocal atherosclerotic plaque (arrow). Extensive mural thrombus (<b>*</b>) is depicted in the involved segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig8a.jpeg" height="1600" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. ACAA in an 81-year-old man with hypertension who presented with acute back pain. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the left cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> and coronal MPR image <b>(c)</b> show a giant aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal LAD. Note the zone of increased attenuation (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>) in the periphery of the aneurysm, a finding suggestive of a more recent hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image further shows the anatomic relationship between the LAD aneurysm and regional structures (arrow). The results of a subsequent cardiac catherization helped confirm a giant, partly thrombosed coronary aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig8b.jpeg" height="1229" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. ACAA in an 81-year-old man with hypertension who presented with acute back pain. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the left cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> and coronal MPR image <b>(c)</b> show a giant aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal LAD. Note the zone of increased attenuation (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>) in the periphery of the aneurysm, a finding suggestive of a more recent hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image further shows the anatomic relationship between the LAD aneurysm and regional structures (arrow). The results of a subsequent cardiac catherization helped confirm a giant, partly thrombosed coronary aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig8c.jpeg" height="1229" width="1242" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. ACAA in an 81-year-old man with hypertension who presented with acute back pain. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the left cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> and coronal MPR image <b>(c)</b> show a giant aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal LAD. Note the zone of increased attenuation (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>) in the periphery of the aneurysm, a finding suggestive of a more recent hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image further shows the anatomic relationship between the LAD aneurysm and regional structures (arrow). The results of a subsequent cardiac catherization helped confirm a giant, partly thrombosed coronary aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig8d.jpeg" height="1229" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. ACAA in an 81-year-old man with hypertension who presented with acute back pain. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the left cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> and coronal MPR image <b>(c)</b> show a giant aneurysm (arrowhead) of the proximal LAD. Note the zone of increased attenuation (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>) in the periphery of the aneurysm, a finding suggestive of a more recent hemorrhage. <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image further shows the anatomic relationship between the LAD aneurysm and regional structures (arrow). The results of a subsequent cardiac catherization helped confirm a giant, partly thrombosed coronary aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig9a.jpeg" height="1242" width="1260" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Multiple ACAAs in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the RCA <b>(b)</b> show aneurysms of the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i> (arrowheads on <b>a</b>) and the RCA (arrowheads on <b>b</b>). The proximal LAD is occluded (arrow on <b>a</b>) just beyond its bifurcation from the left main coronary artery. <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows dilatation (arrows) of the proximal RCA and the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(d)</b> MPR CT angiographic image obtained in the vertical long axis shows the occluded LAD (arrow) and ventricular remodeling of the anterior wall and ventricular apex from a prior myocardial infarct. <b>(e)</b> Curved planar reformatted CT angiographic image of the RCA shows focal regions of aneurysmal involvement and subtle eccentric calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig9b.jpeg" height="1242" width="1242" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Multiple ACAAs in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the RCA <b>(b)</b> show aneurysms of the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i> (arrowheads on <b>a</b>) and the RCA (arrowheads on <b>b</b>). The proximal LAD is occluded (arrow on <b>a</b>) just beyond its bifurcation from the left main coronary artery. <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows dilatation (arrows) of the proximal RCA and the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(d)</b> MPR CT angiographic image obtained in the vertical long axis shows the occluded LAD (arrow) and ventricular remodeling of the anterior wall and ventricular apex from a prior myocardial infarct. <b>(e)</b> Curved planar reformatted CT angiographic image of the RCA shows focal regions of aneurysmal involvement and subtle eccentric calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig9c.jpeg" height="1242" width="1192" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Multiple ACAAs in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the RCA <b>(b)</b> show aneurysms of the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i> (arrowheads on <b>a</b>) and the RCA (arrowheads on <b>b</b>). The proximal LAD is occluded (arrow on <b>a</b>) just beyond its bifurcation from the left main coronary artery. <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows dilatation (arrows) of the proximal RCA and the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(d)</b> MPR CT angiographic image obtained in the vertical long axis shows the occluded LAD (arrow) and ventricular remodeling of the anterior wall and ventricular apex from a prior myocardial infarct. <b>(e)</b> Curved planar reformatted CT angiographic image of the RCA shows focal regions of aneurysmal involvement and subtle eccentric calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig9d.jpeg" height="1356" width="1356" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Multiple ACAAs in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the RCA <b>(b)</b> show aneurysms of the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i> (arrowheads on <b>a</b>) and the RCA (arrowheads on <b>b</b>). The proximal LAD is occluded (arrow on <b>a</b>) just beyond its bifurcation from the left main coronary artery. <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows dilatation (arrows) of the proximal RCA and the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(d)</b> MPR CT angiographic image obtained in the vertical long axis shows the occluded LAD (arrow) and ventricular remodeling of the anterior wall and ventricular apex from a prior myocardial infarct. <b>(e)</b> Curved planar reformatted CT angiographic image of the RCA shows focal regions of aneurysmal involvement and subtle eccentric calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig9e.jpeg" height="1356" width="1088" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Multiple ACAAs in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained after injection of the RCA <b>(b)</b> show aneurysms of the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i> (arrowheads on <b>a</b>) and the RCA (arrowheads on <b>b</b>). The proximal LAD is occluded (arrow on <b>a</b>) just beyond its bifurcation from the left main coronary artery. <i>LD</i> = left diagonal artery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows dilatation (arrows) of the proximal RCA and the proximal left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(d)</b> MPR CT angiographic image obtained in the vertical long axis shows the occluded LAD (arrow) and ventricular remodeling of the anterior wall and ventricular apex from a prior myocardial infarct. <b>(e)</b> Curved planar reformatted CT angiographic image of the RCA shows focal regions of aneurysmal involvement and subtle eccentric calcification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig10a.jpeg" height="1696" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Congenital or idiopathic CAA in a 26-year-old woman who presented with dysarthria and right upper extremity weakness. At MR imaging, a subacute cerebral infarct was demonstrated, a finding that prompted a search for an embolic source. <b>(a)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the right cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and right ventricular outflow tract <b>(c)</b> steady-state free precession MR images (30.3/1.47 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]; 70° flip angle; field of view [FOV], 360 × 360) show a large hyperintense epicardial mass (<b>*</b>) compressing the right atrium and right ventricle. The RCA courses just anterior to the mass (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a large aneurysm of the RCA; a fistulous connection to the right atrium (arrowhead) was found at surgery. In addition, the patient had a patent foramen ovale, which presumably facilitated paradoxical embolism from the coronary aneurysm. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Upper scale is in centimeters; lower scale is in inches.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig10b.jpeg" height="1230" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Congenital or idiopathic CAA in a 26-year-old woman who presented with dysarthria and right upper extremity weakness. At MR imaging, a subacute cerebral infarct was demonstrated, a finding that prompted a search for an embolic source. <b>(a)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the right cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and right ventricular outflow tract <b>(c)</b> steady-state free precession MR images (30.3/1.47 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]; 70° flip angle; field of view [FOV], 360 × 360) show a large hyperintense epicardial mass (<b>*</b>) compressing the right atrium and right ventricle. The RCA courses just anterior to the mass (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a large aneurysm of the RCA; a fistulous connection to the right atrium (arrowhead) was found at surgery. In addition, the patient had a patent foramen ovale, which presumably facilitated paradoxical embolism from the coronary aneurysm. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Upper scale is in centimeters; lower scale is in inches.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig10c.jpeg" height="1230" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Congenital or idiopathic CAA in a 26-year-old woman who presented with dysarthria and right upper extremity weakness. At MR imaging, a subacute cerebral infarct was demonstrated, a finding that prompted a search for an embolic source. <b>(a)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the right cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and right ventricular outflow tract <b>(c)</b> steady-state free precession MR images (30.3/1.47 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]; 70° flip angle; field of view [FOV], 360 × 360) show a large hyperintense epicardial mass (<b>*</b>) compressing the right atrium and right ventricle. The RCA courses just anterior to the mass (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a large aneurysm of the RCA; a fistulous connection to the right atrium (arrowhead) was found at surgery. In addition, the patient had a patent foramen ovale, which presumably facilitated paradoxical embolism from the coronary aneurysm. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Upper scale is in centimeters; lower scale is in inches.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig10d.jpeg" height="1230" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Congenital or idiopathic CAA in a 26-year-old woman who presented with dysarthria and right upper extremity weakness. At MR imaging, a subacute cerebral infarct was demonstrated, a finding that prompted a search for an embolic source. <b>(a)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows a contour abnormality of the right cardiac border (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis <b>(b)</b> and right ventricular outflow tract <b>(c)</b> steady-state free precession MR images (30.3/1.47 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]; 70° flip angle; field of view [FOV], 360 × 360) show a large hyperintense epicardial mass (<b>*</b>) compressing the right atrium and right ventricle. The RCA courses just anterior to the mass (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a large aneurysm of the RCA; a fistulous connection to the right atrium (arrowhead) was found at surgery. In addition, the patient had a patent foramen ovale, which presumably facilitated paradoxical embolism from the coronary aneurysm. <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. (Upper scale is in centimeters; lower scale is in inches.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig11a.jpeg" height="1298" width="1298" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a)</b> Oblique axial CT angiographic image shows a CAA (arrow) with eccentric thrombus and a partly calcified rim in the proximal LAD. <b>(b)</b> MPR CT angiographic image shows a partly calcified aneurysm with eccentric thrombus (arrowhead) in the proximal left circumflex coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> MPR CT angiographic image shows ectasia (arrow) of the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig11b.jpeg" height="1298" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a)</b> Oblique axial CT angiographic image shows a CAA (arrow) with eccentric thrombus and a partly calcified rim in the proximal LAD. <b>(b)</b> MPR CT angiographic image shows a partly calcified aneurysm with eccentric thrombus (arrowhead) in the proximal left circumflex coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> MPR CT angiographic image shows ectasia (arrow) of the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig11c.jpeg" height="1298" width="1067" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a)</b> Oblique axial CT angiographic image shows a CAA (arrow) with eccentric thrombus and a partly calcified rim in the proximal LAD. <b>(b)</b> MPR CT angiographic image shows a partly calcified aneurysm with eccentric thrombus (arrowhead) in the proximal left circumflex coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> MPR CT angiographic image shows ectasia (arrow) of the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig12a.jpeg" height="1260" width="1260" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, MPR <b>(b)</b>, and vertical long-axis <b>(c)</b>CT angiographic images show rim calcification and complete occlusion of a CAA (arrow) in the proximal LAD. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the surface anatomy of the proximal LAD aneurysm (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig12b.jpeg" height="1260" width="1210" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, MPR <b>(b)</b>, and vertical long-axis <b>(c)</b>CT angiographic images show rim calcification and complete occlusion of a CAA (arrow) in the proximal LAD. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the surface anatomy of the proximal LAD aneurysm (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig12c.jpeg" height="1260" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, MPR <b>(b)</b>, and vertical long-axis <b>(c)</b>CT angiographic images show rim calcification and complete occlusion of a CAA (arrow) in the proximal LAD. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the surface anatomy of the proximal LAD aneurysm (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig12d.jpeg" height="1579" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>, MPR <b>(b)</b>, and vertical long-axis <b>(c)</b>CT angiographic images show rim calcification and complete occlusion of a CAA (arrow) in the proximal LAD. <b>(d)</b> Volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the surface anatomy of the proximal LAD aneurysm (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig13a.jpeg" height="1488" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Kawasaki disease in an asymptomatic 28-year-old patient. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volumetric CT angiographic image shows a large aneurysm (arrowhead) at the juncture of the LAD and the left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique magnified and collimated angiographic image obtained after cardiac catheterization with select injection of the left circumflex coronary artery shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with no angiographic evidence of thrombosis within the aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig13b.jpeg" height="1488" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Kawasaki disease in an asymptomatic 28-year-old patient. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volumetric CT angiographic image shows a large aneurysm (arrowhead) at the juncture of the LAD and the left circumflex coronary artery <i>(LCx)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique magnified and collimated angiographic image obtained after cardiac catheterization with select injection of the left circumflex coronary artery shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with no angiographic evidence of thrombosis within the aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig14a.jpeg" height="1411" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Kawasaki disease. Oblique sagittal thick MPR <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images show a partly thrombosed aneurysm (arrowhead) in the RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig14b.jpeg" height="1411" width="1411" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Kawasaki disease. Oblique sagittal thick MPR <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images show a partly thrombosed aneurysm (arrowhead) in the RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig15a.jpeg" height="1066" width="1390" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained just inferior to <b>a</b>) highlighting the aneurysm in the LAD <b>(a)</b> and the aneurysm in the RCA <b>(b)</b> show multiple rim-calcified aneurysms with eccentric thrombus (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Spider MPR CT angiographic image shows a global view of multiple aneurysms within all three coronary arteries. <i>D1</i> = first diagonal branch, <i>LCX</i> = left circumflex coronary artery, <i>M1</i> = first obtuse marginal branch; <i>OM</i> = obtuse marginal branch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig15b.jpeg" height="1066" width="1064" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained just inferior to <b>a</b>) highlighting the aneurysm in the LAD <b>(a)</b> and the aneurysm in the RCA <b>(b)</b> show multiple rim-calcified aneurysms with eccentric thrombus (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Spider MPR CT angiographic image shows a global view of multiple aneurysms within all three coronary arteries. <i>D1</i> = first diagonal branch, <i>LCX</i> = left circumflex coronary artery, <i>M1</i> = first obtuse marginal branch; <i>OM</i> = obtuse marginal branch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig15c.jpeg" height="1066" width="1247" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Kawasaki disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained just inferior to <b>a</b>) highlighting the aneurysm in the LAD <b>(a)</b> and the aneurysm in the RCA <b>(b)</b> show multiple rim-calcified aneurysms with eccentric thrombus (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Spider MPR CT angiographic image shows a global view of multiple aneurysms within all three coronary arteries. <i>D1</i> = first diagonal branch, <i>LCX</i> = left circumflex coronary artery, <i>M1</i> = first obtuse marginal branch; <i>OM</i> = obtuse marginal branch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig16a.jpeg" height="1538" width="1538" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 28-year-old patient. Oblique sagittal MPR <b>(a)</b> and three-dimensional volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images show ectasia of the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow) and the LAD (arrowhead on <b>b</b>). The patient had minimal atherosclerotic disease and no focal coronary artery luminal narrowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig16b.jpeg" height="1538" width="1111" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 28-year-old patient. Oblique sagittal MPR <b>(a)</b> and three-dimensional volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images show ectasia of the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow) and the LAD (arrowhead on <b>b</b>). The patient had minimal atherosclerotic disease and no focal coronary artery luminal narrowing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig17a.jpeg" height="1307" width="1339" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained with select injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and axial collimated CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> show a peripherally calcified aneurysm (arrow) of the distal left main coronary artery and proximal LAD. <b>(c, d)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image <b>(c)</b> and CT angiographic curved planar reconstruction image <b>(d)</b> of the RCA show several CAAs (arrowheads) that contain peripheral calcification and nonocclusive mural thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig17b.jpeg" height="1311" width="1311" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained with select injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and axial collimated CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> show a peripherally calcified aneurysm (arrow) of the distal left main coronary artery and proximal LAD. <b>(c, d)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image <b>(c)</b> and CT angiographic curved planar reconstruction image <b>(d)</b> of the RCA show several CAAs (arrowheads) that contain peripheral calcification and nonocclusive mural thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig17c.jpeg" height="1392" width="959" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained with select injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and axial collimated CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> show a peripherally calcified aneurysm (arrow) of the distal left main coronary artery and proximal LAD. <b>(c, d)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image <b>(c)</b> and CT angiographic curved planar reconstruction image <b>(d)</b> of the RCA show several CAAs (arrowheads) that contain peripheral calcification and nonocclusive mural thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig17d.jpeg" height="1391" width="1690" aria-labelledby="fig17d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17d</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Right anterior oblique conventional angiographic image obtained with select injection of the left main coronary artery <b>(a)</b> and axial collimated CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> show a peripherally calcified aneurysm (arrow) of the distal left main coronary artery and proximal LAD. <b>(c, d)</b> Left anterior oblique conventional angiographic image <b>(c)</b> and CT angiographic curved planar reconstruction image <b>(d)</b> of the RCA show several CAAs (arrowheads) that contain peripheral calcification and nonocclusive mural thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig17d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig18a.jpeg" height="1200" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Takayasu arteritis in a 31-year-old patient with atypical chest pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained slightly superior to <b>a</b>) at the takeoff of the RCA <b>(a)</b> and at the takeoff of the left main coronary artery <b>(b)</b> show CAAs in the proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection CT angiographic image of the abdomen and upper pelvis shows aneurysms of the renal arteries (arrows) and hepatic artery (arrowhead). The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed necrotizing aortitis and helped confirm the clinical diagnosis of Takayasu arteritis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig18b.jpeg" height="1200" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Takayasu arteritis in a 31-year-old patient with atypical chest pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained slightly superior to <b>a</b>) at the takeoff of the RCA <b>(a)</b> and at the takeoff of the left main coronary artery <b>(b)</b> show CAAs in the proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection CT angiographic image of the abdomen and upper pelvis shows aneurysms of the renal arteries (arrows) and hepatic artery (arrowhead). The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed necrotizing aortitis and helped confirm the clinical diagnosis of Takayasu arteritis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig18c.jpeg" height="1784" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Takayasu arteritis in a 31-year-old patient with atypical chest pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained slightly superior to <b>a</b>) at the takeoff of the RCA <b>(a)</b> and at the takeoff of the left main coronary artery <b>(b)</b> show CAAs in the proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection CT angiographic image of the abdomen and upper pelvis shows aneurysms of the renal arteries (arrows) and hepatic artery (arrowhead). The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed necrotizing aortitis and helped confirm the clinical diagnosis of Takayasu arteritis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig19a.jpeg" height="1176" width="1176" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Takayasu arteritis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial steady-state free precession MR image (35/1.54; 60° flip angle; FOV, 256 × 256) <b>(b)</b> depict a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) depicts an aneurysm of the left main coronary artery, as well as numerous aneurysms of both subclavian arteries (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) obtained 6 months later, after therapy, shows resolution of the previous multifocal aneurysms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig19b.jpeg" height="1176" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Takayasu arteritis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial steady-state free precession MR image (35/1.54; 60° flip angle; FOV, 256 × 256) <b>(b)</b> depict a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) depicts an aneurysm of the left main coronary artery, as well as numerous aneurysms of both subclavian arteries (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) obtained 6 months later, after therapy, shows resolution of the previous multifocal aneurysms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig19c.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Takayasu arteritis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial steady-state free precession MR image (35/1.54; 60° flip angle; FOV, 256 × 256) <b>(b)</b> depict a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) depicts an aneurysm of the left main coronary artery, as well as numerous aneurysms of both subclavian arteries (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) obtained 6 months later, after therapy, shows resolution of the previous multifocal aneurysms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig19d.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig19d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span>. Takayasu arteritis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image <b>(a)</b> and axial steady-state free precession MR image (35/1.54; 60° flip angle; FOV, 256 × 256) <b>(b)</b> depict a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the left main coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Coronal three-dimensional MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) depicts an aneurysm of the left main coronary artery, as well as numerous aneurysms of both subclavian arteries (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Coronal MR angiographic image (2.63/0.97; 25° flip angle; FOV, 300 ×300) obtained 6 months later, after therapy, shows resolution of the previous multifocal aneurysms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig20.jpeg" height="1200" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Marfan syndrome. Oblique axial CT angiographic image shows repair of an ascending aortic aneurysm associated with a CAA (arrow) in the mid LAD. (Image courtesy of Andrew J. Bierhals, MD, MPH, Mallinckrodt Institute of Radiology, Washington University School of Medicine, St Louis, Mo.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig21a.jpeg" height="1474" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. CAA in a 65-year-old patient with a history of neurofibromatosis type 1 who presented with mediastinal hemorrhage without a definitive source, considerable chest pain, and hypotension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained superior to <b>a</b>) show ectasia of the LAD (arrow on <b>a</b>) and mediastinal hemorrhage (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>). A small aneurysm of an aotic collateral branch is depicted within the region of hemorrhage as a focus of contrast material (arrow on <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal MPR CT angiographic image shows a large intercostal aneurysm (arrow) and a subtle smaller intercostal aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Scout CT image shows numerous neurofibromas involving the subcutaneous tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig21b.jpeg" height="1474" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. CAA in a 65-year-old patient with a history of neurofibromatosis type 1 who presented with mediastinal hemorrhage without a definitive source, considerable chest pain, and hypotension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained superior to <b>a</b>) show ectasia of the LAD (arrow on <b>a</b>) and mediastinal hemorrhage (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>). A small aneurysm of an aotic collateral branch is depicted within the region of hemorrhage as a focus of contrast material (arrow on <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal MPR CT angiographic image shows a large intercostal aneurysm (arrow) and a subtle smaller intercostal aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Scout CT image shows numerous neurofibromas involving the subcutaneous tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig21c.jpeg" height="1607" width="1334" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span>. CAA in a 65-year-old patient with a history of neurofibromatosis type 1 who presented with mediastinal hemorrhage without a definitive source, considerable chest pain, and hypotension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained superior to <b>a</b>) show ectasia of the LAD (arrow on <b>a</b>) and mediastinal hemorrhage (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>). A small aneurysm of an aotic collateral branch is depicted within the region of hemorrhage as a focus of contrast material (arrow on <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal MPR CT angiographic image shows a large intercostal aneurysm (arrow) and a subtle smaller intercostal aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Scout CT image shows numerous neurofibromas involving the subcutaneous tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig21d.jpeg" height="1607" width="1618" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span>. CAA in a 65-year-old patient with a history of neurofibromatosis type 1 who presented with mediastinal hemorrhage without a definitive source, considerable chest pain, and hypotension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT angiographic images (<b>b</b> obtained superior to <b>a</b>) show ectasia of the LAD (arrow on <b>a</b>) and mediastinal hemorrhage (<b>*</b> on <b>b</b>). A small aneurysm of an aotic collateral branch is depicted within the region of hemorrhage as a focus of contrast material (arrow on <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Coronal MPR CT angiographic image shows a large intercostal aneurysm (arrow) and a subtle smaller intercostal aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Scout CT image shows numerous neurofibromas involving the subcutaneous tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig22a.jpeg" height="1497" width="1727" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Mycotic CAA associated with hypereosinophilia in a 39-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial coronary CT angiographic image shows multiple large CAAs (arrows), some as large as 14 mm in diameter, involving the ostial part of the LAD. <b>(b)</b> Curved MPR CT angiographic image shows associated luminal layered thrombus (arrow) in the proximal LAD, instead of inflammatory tissue. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image better shows the distribution of ectatic and aneurysmal involvement (arrowheads) of the LAD. (Image courtesy of Marcus Chen, MD, National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, Md.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig22b.jpeg" height="1497" width="810" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Mycotic CAA associated with hypereosinophilia in a 39-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial coronary CT angiographic image shows multiple large CAAs (arrows), some as large as 14 mm in diameter, involving the ostial part of the LAD. <b>(b)</b> Curved MPR CT angiographic image shows associated luminal layered thrombus (arrow) in the proximal LAD, instead of inflammatory tissue. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image better shows the distribution of ectatic and aneurysmal involvement (arrowheads) of the LAD. (Image courtesy of Marcus Chen, MD, National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, Md.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig22c.jpeg" height="1497" width="964" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Mycotic CAA associated with hypereosinophilia in a 39-year-old woman who presented with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial coronary CT angiographic image shows multiple large CAAs (arrows), some as large as 14 mm in diameter, involving the ostial part of the LAD. <b>(b)</b> Curved MPR CT angiographic image shows associated luminal layered thrombus (arrow) in the proximal LAD, instead of inflammatory tissue. <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered CT angiographic image better shows the distribution of ectatic and aneurysmal involvement (arrowheads) of the LAD. (Image courtesy of Marcus Chen, MD, National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, Md.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig23a.jpeg" height="1233" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. CAA in association with drug abuse in a 26-year-old man with a history of cocaine abuse who presented with chest pain and a diagnosed non-ST elevation myocardial infarct. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a round enhancing structure (<b>*</b>) in the region of the left circumflex coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Oblique coronal maximum intensity projection CT angiographic image shows an obtuse marginal branch in direct communication with the structure (arrow). <b>(c, d)</b> Short-axis <b>(c)</b> and three-chamber <b>(d)</b> inversion-recovery MR images (435/3.23; 25° flip angle; FOV, 399 × 399) show delayed subendocardial enhancement (arrowhead) in a left circumflex coronary artery distribution. <b>(e)</b> Photograph obtained during surgery shows the aneurysm, with exposure of the ostium (arrow). The patient underwent closure of the CAA and a coronary artery bypass grafting procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170175&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170175/asset/images/large/rg.2018170175.fig23b.jpeg" height="1233" width="1232" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. CAA in association with drug abuse in a 26-year-old man with a history of cocaine abuse who presented with chest pain and a diagnosed non-ST elevation myocardial infarct. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows a round enhancing structure (<b>*</b>) in the region of the left circumflex coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Oblique coronal maximum intensity projection CT angiographic image shows an obtuse marginal branch in direct communication with the structure (arrow). <b>(c, d)</b> Short-axis <b>(c)</b> and three-chamber <b>(d)</b> inversion-recovery MR images (435/3.23; 25° flip angle; FOV, 399 × 399) show delayed subendocardial enhancement (arrowhead) in a left circumflex coronary artery distribution. <b>(e)</b> Photograph obtained during surgery 